    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! L1 and L2 regularization are two methods used to prevent overfitting in machine learning models, but they have different approaches. L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the magnitude of coefficients. This can lead to some coefficients being zero, effectively performing feature selection. On the other hand, L2 regularization, also known as Ridge, adds a penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of coefficients, which tends to shrink the coefficients but rarely sets them to zero. You might choose L1 if you want to reduce the number of features in your model, while L2 is better when you want to keep all features but reduce their impact.",
